WEBVTT

﻿1
00:00:19.876 --> 00:00:23.489
You might think there are many things that I can't do
可能你们认为有许多事情是我不能完成的

2
00:00:23.513 --> 00:00:25.424
because I cannot see.
因为我看不见

3
00:00:26.146 --> 00:00:27.794
That's largely true.
很大程度上来说，这是事实

4
00:00:27.818 --> 00:00:30.301
Actually, I just needed to have a bit of help
比如像刚才我需要一些帮助

5
00:00:30.325 --> 00:00:32.159
to come up to the stage.
才能走上这个讲台

6
00:00:32.183 --> 00:00:35.111
But there is also a lot that I can do.
但也有很多事情是我能够完成的

7
00:00:35.550 --> 00:00:38.962
This is me rock climbing for the first time.
这个，是我第一次攀岩

8
00:00:38.986 --> 00:00:43.063
Actually, I love sports and I can play many sports,
实际上我喜欢运动，我也能够完成很多运动

9
00:00:43.087 --> 00:00:48.469
like swimming, skiing, skating, scuba diving, running and so on.
例如游泳，滑雪，溜冰， 水肺潜水，跑步，等等。

10
00:00:49.202 --> 00:00:51.113
But there is one limitation:
但是总有一个限制:

11
00:00:51.965 --> 00:00:53.724
somebody needs to help me.
我需要旁人的帮助。

12
00:00:54.334 --> 00:00:56.446
I want to be independent.
我想要自己来做。

13
00:00:57.561 --> 00:01:02.264
I lost my sight at the age of 14 in a swimming pool accident.
在我14岁的时候， 一次游泳池里的意外让我丧失了视力

14
00:01:02.809 --> 00:01:05.433
I was an active, independent teenager,
曾经的我是一个活泼和独立的人

15
00:01:05.457 --> 00:01:07.873
and suddenly I became blind.
然后却在一瞬间变成了盲人

16
00:01:08.660 --> 00:01:12.724
The hardest thing for me was losing my independence.
对我来说最困难的事情是失去了独立的能力

17
00:01:13.420 --> 00:01:18.827
Things that until then seemed simple became almost impossible to do alone.
曾经看起来很简单的事情 都变得几乎不可能完成一样

18
00:01:19.782 --> 00:01:23.523
For example, one of my challenges was textbooks.
举个例子，其中一个挑战就是读书

19
00:01:23.904 --> 00:01:26.654
Back then, there were no personal computers,
在那个时候，没有个人电脑

20
00:01:26.678 --> 00:01:29.115
no Internet, no smartphones.
没有网络，没有智能手机

21
00:01:29.139 --> 00:01:34.572
So I had to ask one of my two brothers to read me textbooks,
所以我不得不请求我其中一个哥哥来读给我听

22
00:01:34.596 --> 00:01:38.072
and I had to create my own books in Braille.
并自己把书翻译成盲文

23
00:01:38.473 --> 00:01:39.826
Can you imagine?
你能想象这个画面吗？

24
00:01:40.423 --> 00:01:43.542
Of course, my brothers were not happy about it,
当然，我的哥哥们对此并不乐意

25
00:01:43.566 --> 00:01:47.389
and later, I noticed they were not there whenever I needed them.
后来我发现， 每当我需要他们的时候他们就不见人影了

26
00:01:47.413 --> 00:01:48.414
(Laughter)
(笑)

27
00:01:48.438 --> 00:01:52.230
I think they tried to stay away from me.
我想他们刻意离我远一点

28
00:01:52.254 --> 00:01:53.608
I don't blame them.
我并不责怪他们

29
00:01:54.401 --> 00:01:58.172
I really wanted to be freed from relying on someone.
我真心希望自己不需要依赖任何人

30
00:01:58.980 --> 00:02:02.889
That became my strong desire to ignite innovation.
这变成我想要带来创新最强大的动力

31
00:02:03.920 --> 00:02:06.606
Jump ahead to the mid-1980s.
直到80年代中期

32
00:02:06.630 --> 00:02:09.376
I got to know cutting-edge technologies
我见识到了先进的科技后

33
00:02:09.400 --> 00:02:11.497
and I thought to myself,
联想到了我自己

34
00:02:11.521 --> 00:02:15.140
how come there is no computer technology
为什么没有一种电脑技术

35
00:02:15.164 --> 00:02:17.290
to create books in Braille?
能用来生成盲文书籍呢？

36
00:02:18.108 --> 00:02:22.472
These amazing technologies must be able to also help people
这些令人惊叹的科技也应该能够用来帮助

37
00:02:22.496 --> 00:02:24.895
with limitations like myself.
像我一样有缺陷的人们

38
00:02:25.625 --> 00:02:29.437
That's the moment my innovation journey began.
那就是我创新历程的开端

39
00:02:30.506 --> 00:02:34.360
I started developing digital book technologies,
我开始开发电子书技术

40
00:02:34.384 --> 00:02:39.677
such as a digital Braille editor, digital Braille dictionary
比如电子盲文编辑器，电子盲文字典

41
00:02:39.701 --> 00:02:42.447
and a digital Braille library network.
和电子盲文图书网

42
00:02:42.998 --> 00:02:47.366
Today, every student who is visually impaired can read textbooks,
在今天，每一个有视力障碍的学生都能

43
00:02:47.390 --> 00:02:51.217
by using personal computers and mobile devices,
通过个人电脑和移动设备

44
00:02:51.241 --> 00:02:53.326
in Braille or in voice.
来阅读盲文或听有声读物

45
00:02:53.818 --> 00:02:55.954
This may not surprise you,
你不会为此感到惊讶，

46
00:02:55.978 --> 00:03:01.038
since everyone now has digital books in their tablets in 2015.
因为现在是2015年， 每一个人的平板电脑里面都有电子书

47
00:03:01.062 --> 00:03:06.909
But Braille went digital many years before digital books,
但是大约30年前，也就是80年代末，

48
00:03:06.933 --> 00:03:12.165
already in the late 1980s, almost 30 years ago.
电子盲文已经出现，这远早于电子书

49
00:03:13.062 --> 00:03:16.861
Strong and specific needs of the blind people
盲人的这种强烈和特殊的需求

50
00:03:16.885 --> 00:03:22.528
made this opportunity to create digital books way back then.
促成了早年电子书的发明

51
00:03:23.163 --> 00:03:28.169
And this is actually not the first time this happened,
而且这并不是第一次出现这样的发明

52
00:03:28.193 --> 00:03:34.283
because history shows us accessibility ignites innovation.
历史上就有为了方便残障人士 启发了创新诞生的例子

53
00:03:35.287 --> 00:03:39.304
The telephone was invented while developing a communication tool
电话的发明是为了开发一种

54
00:03:39.328 --> 00:03:41.195
for hearing impaired people.
方便听力障碍人群交流的工具

55
00:03:41.557 --> 00:03:46.977
Some keyboards were also invented to help people with disabilities.
某些键盘也是为了帮助有残疾的人士而发明的

56
00:03:48.627 --> 00:03:52.104
Now I'm going to give you another example from my own life.
现在我来告诉你们一个我生活中的例子。

57
00:03:52.508 --> 00:03:56.771
In the '90s, people around me started talking about the Internet
在90年代，我身边的人开始谈论

58
00:03:56.795 --> 00:03:58.238
and web browsing.
因特网和浏览网页

59
00:03:58.715 --> 00:04:01.587
I remember the first time I went on the web.
我记得第一次上网时

60
00:04:01.968 --> 00:04:03.556
I was astonished.
我惊呆了

61
00:04:04.172 --> 00:04:08.279
I could access newspapers at any time and every day.
我能够每天随时浏览报纸

62
00:04:08.630 --> 00:04:12.486
I could even search for any information by myself.
我甚至能通过我自己搜索到任何信息

63
00:04:12.995 --> 00:04:18.809
I desperately wanted to help the blind people have access to the Internet,
我迫切的想要帮助其他的盲人上网

64
00:04:18.833 --> 00:04:24.139
and I found ways to render the web into synthesized voice,
我找到了能够把网页内容合成成声音的方法

65
00:04:24.163 --> 00:04:27.933
which dramatically simplified the user interface.
这大大的简化了用户界面

66
00:04:28.505 --> 00:04:33.915
This led me to develop the Home Page Reader in 1997,
这使我在1997年开发了"首页阅读器"

67
00:04:33.939 --> 00:04:38.832
first in Japanese and later, translated into 11 languages.
并从最开始的日语普及到了11种语言

68
00:04:39.604 --> 00:04:42.181
When I developed the Home Page Reader,
当我在开发"首页阅读器"的时候

69
00:04:42.205 --> 00:04:45.134
I got many comments from users.
我收到了许多来自于用户的建议

70
00:04:45.729 --> 00:04:48.255
One that I strongly remember said,
其中有一个我印象深刻，他说:

71
00:04:48.852 --> 00:04:54.100
"For me, the Internet is a small window to the world."
"对我来说，网络是打开世界的窗口。"

72
00:04:55.005 --> 00:04:57.946
It was a revolutionary moment for the blind.
这对于盲人来说是一个革新的时刻。

73
00:04:58.950 --> 00:05:01.127
The cyber world became accessible,
网络世界变得触手可及

74
00:05:01.151 --> 00:05:05.821
and this technology that we created for the blind has many uses,
并且有许多的用户使用我们这项 本来是为盲人开发的技术

75
00:05:05.845 --> 00:05:07.820
way beyond what I imagined.
多到超过我的预想

76
00:05:08.359 --> 00:05:12.505
It can help drivers listen to their emails
它能够帮助司机阅读邮件

77
00:05:12.529 --> 00:05:16.802
or it can help you listen to a recipe while cooking.
它能在你做饭的时候帮你阅读菜谱

78
00:05:17.936 --> 00:05:20.446
Today, I am more independent,
今天，我变得更加独立了

79
00:05:20.470 --> 00:05:22.786
but it is still not enough.
但还远远不够

80
00:05:23.488 --> 00:05:29.343
For example, when I approached the stage just now, I needed assistance.
例如我刚刚要走上讲台的时候， 我还是需要协助

81
00:05:30.232 --> 00:05:33.653
My goal is to come up here independently.
我的目标是靠我自己走上来

82
00:05:33.967 --> 00:05:35.494
And not just here.
而且不仅仅只是走上这个讲台

83
00:05:35.811 --> 00:05:41.630
My goal is to be able to travel and do things that are simple to you.
我的目标是去旅行， 去完成对你们来说很容易的事情

84
00:05:42.458 --> 00:05:45.267
OK, now let me show you the latest technologies.
好了，现在让我来给你们展示一些最新的科技

85
00:05:45.291 --> 00:05:48.815
This is a smartphone app that we are working on.
这是我们目前正在开发的一个智能手机客户端

86
00:05:50.445 --> 00:05:54.079
(Video) Electronic voice: 51 feet to the door, and keep straight.
(视频)电子语音: 距离门口51英尺，直行

87
00:05:57.522 --> 00:06:00.645
EV: Take the two doors to go out. The door is on your right.
电子语音:打开两扇门出去。门在你右边

88
00:06:07.551 --> 00:06:09.489
EV: Nick is approaching. Looks so happy.
电子语音:尼克正在朝你走来。 他看起来很高兴。

89
00:06:09.513 --> 00:06:10.718
Chieko Asakawa: Hi, Nick!
浅川智惠子:你好，尼克

90
00:06:10.742 --> 00:06:11.743
(Laughter)
(笑声)

91
00:06:11.767 --> 00:06:13.910
CA: Where are you going? You look so happy.
浅川智惠子:你要去哪儿？ 你看起来很开心

92
00:06:13.934 --> 00:06:16.047
Nick: Oh -- well, my paper just got accepted.
尼克: 啊，我的文章刚刚被接受啦

93
00:06:16.071 --> 00:06:17.718
CA: That's great! Congratulations.
浅川智惠子:真棒！祝贺你

94
00:06:17.742 --> 00:06:21.393
Nick: Thanks. Wait -- how'd you know it was me, and that I look happy?
尼克: 谢谢。等等，你怎么知道是我， 并知道我很高兴的？

95
00:06:21.417 --> 00:06:22.767
(Chieko and Nick laugh)
(浅川智惠子和 尼克 大笑)

96
00:06:22.791 --> 00:06:23.950
Man: Hi.
路人:你好

97
00:06:23.974 --> 00:06:25.691
(Laughter)
(笑声)

98
00:06:25.715 --> 00:06:26.866
CA: Oh ... hi.
浅川智惠子:你好

99
00:06:26.890 --> 00:06:29.207
EV: He is not talking to you, but on his phone.
电子语音: 他没有跟你讲话，他在讲电话

100
00:06:36.254 --> 00:06:37.436
EV: Potato chips.
电子语音: 薯片。

101
00:06:44.979 --> 00:06:46.582
EV: Dark chocolate with almonds.
电子语音: 杏仁黑巧克力。

102
00:06:47.975 --> 00:06:51.496
EV: You gained 5 pounds since yesterday; take apple instead of chocolate.
电子语音: 你比昨天重了5磅。 你应该拿起苹果，放下巧克力。

103
00:06:51.520 --> 00:06:53.686
(Laughter)
(笑声)

104
00:06:54.276 --> 00:06:55.588
EV: Approaching.
电子语音: 正在靠近

105
00:06:59.858 --> 00:07:01.034
EV: You arrived.
电子语音: 到达目的地

106
00:07:02.759 --> 00:07:03.998
CA: Now ...
浅川智惠子:现在。。。

107
00:07:04.022 --> 00:07:07.950
(Applause)
(掌声)

108
00:07:07.974 --> 00:07:09.165
Thank you.
谢谢

109
00:07:09.189 --> 00:07:12.087
So now the app navigates me
所以现在这个应用通过分析

110
00:07:12.111 --> 00:07:16.127
by analyzing beacon signals and smartphone sensors
指标讯号和手机感应来引导我

111
00:07:16.151 --> 00:07:21.287
and permits me to move around indoor and outdoor environments
并让我能够靠我自己在室内和之外

112
00:07:21.311 --> 00:07:22.899
all by myself.
的环境间移动

113
00:07:22.923 --> 00:07:27.771
But the computer vision part that showed who is approaching,
但是指示我谁在靠近， 情绪如何的电脑视觉部分

114
00:07:27.795 --> 00:07:31.301
in which mood -- we are still working on that part.
我们还在努力改进

115
00:07:32.071 --> 00:07:38.477
And recognizing facial expressions is very important for me to be social.
这个面部表情识别功能 对我的社交生活非常重要

116
00:07:39.218 --> 00:07:45.384
So now the fusions of technologies are ready to help me
所以，现在科技的融合已经帮助我

117
00:07:45.408 --> 00:07:47.088
see the real world.
看到了真实的世界

118
00:07:47.740 --> 00:07:50.969
We call this cognitive assistance.
我们称它为认知协助

119
00:07:51.641 --> 00:07:54.960
It understands our surrounding world
它帮助我们理解我们周围的世界

120
00:07:54.984 --> 00:08:01.201
and whispers to me in voice or sends a vibration to my fingers.
并且通过语音或者手指的震动来告诉我

121
00:08:01.908 --> 00:08:07.972
Cognitive assistance will augment missing or weakened abilities --
认知协助可以增强我们缺少或弱化的能力——

122
00:08:07.996 --> 00:08:10.627
in other words, our five senses.
换句话说，就是我们的五官

123
00:08:11.284 --> 00:08:14.595
This technology is only in an early stage,
这种科技还在初级阶段

124
00:08:14.619 --> 00:08:19.396
but eventually, I'll be able to find a classroom on campus,
但最终，我能够找到校园里的一间教室

125
00:08:19.420 --> 00:08:21.174
enjoy window shopping
能够享受橱窗购物

126
00:08:21.198 --> 00:08:25.059
or find a nice restaurant while walking along a street.
或者在漫步的时候找到一间不错的餐厅

127
00:08:25.908 --> 00:08:30.535
It will be amazing if I can find you on the street before you notice me.
在大街上我能够在你注意我之前就找到你， 那将是多么让人惊讶

128
00:08:31.415 --> 00:08:35.202
It will become my best buddy, and yours.
它会变成我最好的伙伴， 也会是你最好的伙伴

129
00:08:36.128 --> 00:08:39.718
So, this really is a great challenge.
所以，这真的是一个挑战

130
00:08:40.215 --> 00:08:44.184
It is a challenge that needs collaboration,
一个需要合作的挑战

131
00:08:44.208 --> 00:08:47.110
which is why we are creating an open community
这个合作正是我们创造一个促进研究交流

132
00:08:47.134 --> 00:08:49.993
to accelerate research activities.
的开放社区的目的

133
00:08:51.012 --> 00:08:55.910
Just this morning, we announced the open-source fundamental technologies
就在今天早上，我们发布了开源的基础技术

134
00:08:55.934 --> 00:08:57.561
you just saw in the video.
就是你们刚刚在视频里面看到的

135
00:08:58.307 --> 00:09:01.071
The frontier is the real world.
前沿就是真实的世界

136
00:09:01.698 --> 00:09:06.111
The blind community is exploring this technical frontier
盲人团体正在发掘这一技术的前沿

137
00:09:06.135 --> 00:09:07.841
and the pathfinder.
和探路者

138
00:09:08.379 --> 00:09:12.117
I hope to work with you to explore the new era,
我希望和你们一起来探索这个新的纪元

139
00:09:12.141 --> 00:09:15.228
and the next time that I'm on this stage,
也希望下次当我站在这个讲台上的时候

140
00:09:15.252 --> 00:09:17.666
through technology and innovation,
在科技和创新的帮助下

141
00:09:17.690 --> 00:09:19.715
I will be able to walk up here
我能够完全靠我自己

142
00:09:19.739 --> 00:09:21.335
all by myself.
走到这里

143
00:09:21.359 --> 00:09:22.598
Thank you so much.
谢谢大家

144
00:09:22.622 --> 00:09:28.240
(Applause)
(掌声)

